     Now to explore (no pun intended) another facet of exploration, that
is searching.  Searching an area or a feature of that area is a way
of gaining even more specific information about it than examining
will do, that is when there is actually something more to be seen.
Quite frequently you will receive the default message when
you search, namely 'You search <argument> and see nothing.'  All this
means is that the builder has not placed anything special to be
noticed in the specific spot you are searching.  There very
well could be something to be seen or found in the area by
means of a search, but that you have not selected the correct
component of the room to give the once over lightly.  For example,
you might be trapped in a prison cell and when you 'search walls'
you receive the default message, but when you 'search north wall' you
find a secret passage out of your predicament.  Thus you must be sure to
be thorough in your searches of rooms.  Also do not forget that you
need not always provide an argument for your search command.  A rather
generic 'search' will sometimes reveal something about a room which
the room description did not.  Keep searching in mind when exploring
this segment of the quest, and indeed in any quest, and you will
likely be quite successful.
